Does the SOSA ontology define a property for when the observed phenomenon actually occurred (distinct from when the result was recorded)?

trace.code:
# Query for any phenomenonTime usage in the data
result = sparql_query("""
PREFIX sosa: <http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/>
SELECT ?p WHERE {
  GRAPH <http://localhost:8080/graph/observations> {
    ?obs a sosa:Observation ;
         ?p ?o .
  }
}
GROUP BY ?p
""")
print("Properties in observations:", result)

answer = """Yes. The SOSA ontology defines **`sosa:phenomenonTime`** as the property for when the observed phenomenon actually occurred in the real world, which is distinct from `sosa:resultTime`.

- **`sosa:phenomenonTime`**: The time that the result of an Observation applies to the FeatureOfInterest — i.e., when the real-world phenomenon occurred. Its range is a `time:TemporalEntity` (from OWL-Time), supporting both instants and intervals.
- **`sosa:resultTime`**: The time when the observation result was produced or recorded by the sensor.

For example, a sensor might record (resultTime) on Monday a temperature spike that actually occurred (phenomenonTime) the previous Friday. This mirrors the transaction-time vs. valid-time distinction in temporal databases."""

sparql_used = """PREFIX sosa: <http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/>
SELECT ?p WHERE {
  GRAPH <http://localhost:8080/graph/observations> {
    ?obs a sosa:Observation ;
         ?p ?o .
  }
}
GROUP BY ?p"""

sources = [
    "http://www.w3.org/ns/sosa/",
    "https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-ssn/"
]

SUBMIT(answer, sparql_used, sources)

